  "output": "## Performance Analysis ‚Äî `apps/crawler`\n\nThis is a synchronous Python news crawler (not a React app or DB-backed service), so I've mapped your checklist onto what's actually here: repeated I/O work, redundant computation, unbounded growth, and missed caching. Verified against real state ‚Äî `state/lexpress-mg.json` already has **1,257** seen URLs, `malagasynews-mbs` **982**, `newsmada` **879** ‚Äî so the issues below are live, not theoretical.\n\n### 1. O(n¬≤) state rewrite ‚Äî the \"N+1\" of this codebase\n\n`base.py:308-314`, inside `crawl()`'s per-article loop:\n\n```python\nseen.add(url)\nsaved.append(article)\nself._append_article(article)\nstate[\"seen_urls\"] = sorted(seen)      # sorts the WHOLE set, every article\nstate[\"total_saved\"] = state.get(\"total_saved\", 0) + 1\nstate[\"last_run_at\"] = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()\nself._save_state(state)                # json.dumps + full file write, every article\n```\n\nFor every single article saved, this **sorts and re-serializes the entire `seen_urls` history** (already 1,257 entries for lexpress) and rewrites the full JSON file to disk. A run that saves 10 new articles against a 1,257-URL backlog does `sorted()` + `json.dumps()` + a full file write **10 times over the same growing list** ‚Äî this is the crawler's equivalent of an N+1 query, and it gets quadratically worse as `seen_urls` grows across runs (it never shrinks).\n\n**Fix:** keep `seen_urls` as a set in memory, sort only once at the end, and consider keeping `seen` as a `dict`/`set` write append-only rather than a fully re-sorted list:\n\n```python\ndef crawl(self, limit: int = 10, on_save=None) -> list[Article]:\n    state = self._load_state()\n    seen: set[str] = set(state.get(\"seen_urls\", []))\n    saved: list[Article] = []\n    ...\n    for url in self.list_article_urls():\n        ...\n        seen.add(url)\n        saved.append(article)\n        self._append_article(article)\n        state[\"seen_urls\"] = list(seen)          # no sort needed for lookups\n        state[\"total_saved\"] = state.get(\"total_saved\", 0) + 1\n        state[\"last_run_at\"] = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()\n        self._save_state(state)                  # still checkpoints every article (good, keep resumability)\n        ...\n```\n\nSorting was only ever cosmetic (diff-friendliness of the JSON file) ‚Äî if you want that, sort once right before each `_save_state` call is unavoidable per-checkpoint, but dropping `sorted()` removes the O(n log n) cost per article; the `json.dumps`/write is still O(n) per checkpoint but that's inherent to the crash-safe design and is a reasonable tradeoff to keep as-is.\n\nIf checkpoint-per-article throughput ever matters more than crash granularity, an even bigger win is batching: checkpoint every N articles instead of every 1 (trades \"lose 1 article on crash\" for \"lose up to N\").\n\n### 2. Redundant computation: `get_all_text()` called twice per paragraph\n\n`base.py:183-187`:\n\n```python\nbody = \"\\n\\n\".join(\n    p.get_all_text(strip=True)\n    for p in page.css(s.body)\n    if p.get_all_text(strip=True)     # ‚Üê recomputed\n)\n```\n\n`get_all_text(strip=True)` walks the DOM subtree and re-strips text ‚Äî doing it twice per paragraph (once to filter, once to yield) doubles the parsing cost for the article body, which is the single largest per-page cost in `parse_article`. Fix:\n\n```python\nbody = \"\\n\\n\".join(\n    text for text in (p.get_all_text(strip=True) for p in page.css(s.body)) if text\n)\n```\n\n### 3. `list.pop(0)` instead of `deque` in sitemap discovery\n\n`base.py:70-72`, `discover_sitemap_urls`:\n\n```python\nto_visit = [sitemap_url]\nwhile to_visit:\n    current = to_visit.pop(0)   # O(n) shift on a plain list\n```\n\n`Moov.list_article_urls` already uses `collections.deque` correctly (`providers.py:206`) ‚Äî apply the same fix here for consistency. Midi has ~118 sub-sitemaps so today's cost is trivial, but it's a one-line fix (`deque` + `popleft()`) and removes a latent O(n¬≤) if any provider's sitemap index ever grows large.\n\n### 4. Missed caching: Moov fetches every article page twice\n\n`providers.py:216-228` ‚Äî acknowledged in the comment (`each page is fetched twice ‚Äî once here to expand the frontier, once in parse_article`). Since `list_article_urls` already has the fetched `page` object in hand when it discovers a URL, threading that through (e.g., a small `functools.lru_cache`-backed fetch wrapper keyed by URL, or passing the already-fetched page into `parse_article` via an optional param) would halve Moov's network cost. Given the comment frames this as an accepted tradeoff for a \"small site,\" I'd leave it unless Moov's provider becomes a bottleneck ‚Äî but it's the clearest caching opportunity in the codebase.\n\n### 5. Unbounded memory/state growth (the closest thing to a \"leak\" here)\n\n`seen_urls` is loaded entirely into memory and grows forever ‚Äî there's no expiry, cap, or archival. Not a leak in the process sense (each `crawl()` run exits cleanly), but across the project's lifetime `state/*.json` files (already up to 137 KB for malagasynews-mbs) will keep growing linearly with total articles ever crawled, and every run pays the cost of loading + rewriting that whole file. If the providers run for years, consider either:\n- moving `seen_urls` to a lighter format (e.g., a sorted append-only text file of URL hashes) instead of a JSON array rewritten wholesale each checkpoint, or\n- storing a hash set instead of full URLs to cut file size.\n\nNot urgent at current scale (hundreds of KB), but worth flagging since it compounds with issue #1.\n\n### 6. No concurrency ‚Äî biggest actual throughput lever, but a design choice\n\nEvery fetch (`base.py:162-165`, `Fetcher.get`/`StealthyFetcher.fetch`, plus `urllib.request.urlopen` in `_fetch_xml` and `FreeNews.list_article_urls`) is synchronous and sequential ‚Äî one URL at a time, no connection pooling reuse beyond whatever `Fetcher`/`urllib` do internally, no parallel fetch across providers in `main.py`'s `for name in names` loop. For an I/O-bound crawler this is the single biggest lever (a `ThreadPoolExecutor` over independent providers in `main.py`, or over article fetches within a provider run, could plausibly cut wall-clock time by 5-10x). I'm not recommending it outright since `needs_stealth` sites and rate-limit courtesy toward these news sites are real constraints you may be managing deliberately ‚Äî worth a explicit decision rather than a silent change.\n\n---\n\n**Not applicable to this repo:** N+1 DB queries (no database), React re-renders (no React code ‚Äî `apps/crawler` is pure Python), and no evidence of memory leaks in the classic sense (no long-lived process, no unclosed handles ‚Äî file operations use context managers throughout).\n\n**Priority ranking:** #1 (state rewrite) is the highest-value fix ‚Äî it's real, measurable, and gets worse every day the crawler runs. #2 is a free two-line win. #3 is cosmetic-scale today. #4 and #6 are judgment calls depending on how much you value simplicity vs. throughput/politeness toward source sites.\n",
